peror and pope, Protestant and Catholic, pietas and its derivatives in the modern languages bring to literary works multiple contexts of ideological dispute. This book traces the history of the Vergilian ideal from classical Latin to neoclassical English literature. In the process of, it comparatively engages interpretation of a range of literary works diversely responsive to the Aeneid: from the histories and historical epics of the Silver Age, to the medieval mirrors for magistrates, to Renaissance adaptations of Aeneid 4 and 12, and finally to Dryden's complete translation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aAeneas (Legendary character) in literature. 0aDuty in literature. 0aLatin languagexSemantics. 0aLiterature, MedievalxRoman influences. 0aLiterature, ModernxRoman influences. 0aPietas (The Latin word). 0aPiety in literature. 0aTurnus (Legendary character) in literature. 0aVirtue in literature. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / Etymology.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311074526940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271075402zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271075402423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780271075402.jpg  a978-3-11-074526-9  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014b2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK